
A 90-Day Guide for Growing a Mutual Aid Society Without Losing the Foundation
Build deeper before you build bigger.

Purpose of the Next Container
The first 100 days proved that the society could begin.
The next container teaches the society how to continue.
This phase is not about rushing into scale, publicity, or complexity. It is about strengthening the structure that survived the first 100 days and choosing one disciplined growth path.
The society should not ask:
How do we get bigger?
It should ask:
What can we now carry responsibly?
The first container built the foundation.
The next container strengthens the frame.

Core Question
What do we build after Day 100?
After Day 100, the society has evidence.
It knows:
Who returned
 Who disappeared
 What money discipline looked like
 What needs repeated
 What roles worked
 What rules were unclear
 What care teams could carry
 What conflict appeared
 What records were kept
 What first action was completed
 What the group is actually ready for
The next container should be built from that evidence.
Not imagination.
Not hype.
Not pressure.
Not comparison.
Evidence.

The Next Container Sequence
The society should move through this sequence:
Review → Recommit → Repair → Strengthen → Choose → Build → Report
Review
Look honestly at the first 100 days.
Recommit
Confirm who is carrying the next phase.
Repair
Fix what broke or weakened trust.
Strengthen
Improve roles, rules, treasury, records, and meeting rhythm.
Choose
Select one next container.
Build
Work the next 90-day cycle.
Report
Produce the Next Container Report.

The Rule of One
The next container should focus on one major growth path.
Not five.
Not everything.
One.
A society that tries to build every next thing at once will scatter its trust.
Choose one:
Emergency Fund Container
 Business Support Container
 Property Stewardship Container
 Youth Formation Container
 Preparedness Container
 Culture and Creator Ownership Container
 Elder Care and Memory Container
 Leadership Training Container
 Institutional Governance Container
 Regional Connection Container
Pick the one that grows naturally from the first 100 days.

PART ONE: REVIEW THE FIRST CONTAINER

Chapter 1: What Did We Prove?
Core Question
What evidence do we have that we can continue?
Understand
The first 100 days were not about perfection.
They were about proof.
You were testing whether the society could become dependable under light weight before carrying heavier responsibility.
Do not review only money.
Review trust.
Review return.
Review records.
Review care.
Review conflict.
Review capacity.
The first container was successful if it created evidence that the group can continue honestly.
Discuss
Who returned consistently?
What did we complete?
What did we avoid?
What became confusing?
What created trust?
What weakened trust?
What did the first action teach us?
Build: First Container Review
What did we prove?

What held?

What broke?

What surprised us?

What became clearer?

What should we stop doing?

What should we continue?

What should we repair before growing?

Chapter Outputs
[ ] First 100 days reviewed
 [ ] Strengths named
 [ ] Weaknesses named
 [ ] Repair needs identified
 [ ] Growth readiness discussed
Do in Simba
Open the Day 100 Report and add Review Notes.

Chapter 2: Who Is Still Carrying?
Core Question
Who is actually available for the next phase?
Understand
A society should never build on imaginary capacity.
After the first 100 days, some people may be more committed. Some may need rest. Some may need to step back. Some supporters may be ready to become core.
This is not failure.
This is information.
The next container must be built by people who can actually return.
A smaller honest core is stronger than a larger pretend list.
Discuss
Who carried real responsibility?
Who needs rest?
Who needs role rotation?
Who should become core?
Who should become supporter?
What roles are vacant?
